 1. Arrays :
     An array is a fixed-size data structure that stores elements of the same type in contiguous memory locations.     
      int[] arr = {10, 20, 30, 40};
   Internal Working:
        Arrays are stored in continuous memory
        Index-based access → O(1) (very fast)
   JVM stores:
        Base address
        Index offset calculation
   Formula: Address = base + (index * size_of_element)
   Characteristics:
          Feature    	Description
          Size	      Fixed
          Type	      Homogeneous
          Access	    Fast (O(1))
          Memory	    Contiguous
     
  Types of Arrays
      1. Single Dimensional -int[] arr = new int[5];
      2. Multi-Dimensional -int[][] matrix = new int[3][3];
      3. Jagged Array (Different column sizes) - int[][] jagged = new int[3][];
                  jagged[0] = new int[2];
                  jagged[1] = new int[4];
 
  Important Methods (from Arrays class):
        import java.util.Arrays;
        Arrays.sort(arr);        // Sorting
        Arrays.toString(arr);    // Convert to String
        Arrays.binarySearch(arr, 20);
        Arrays.copyOf(arr, 10);
        Arrays.fill(arr, 5);
    
  ✅ Advantages:
        ✔ Fast access
        ✔ Memory efficient
        ✔ Simple structure   
    ❌ Disadvantages:
        ❌ Fixed size
        ❌ Insertion/deletion costly
        ❌ No built-in dynamic behavior   
   Example:
    int[] arr = {5, 2, 8, 1};
    Arrays.sort(arr); 
    for (int num : arr) {
        System.out.println(num);
    }

2. Strings:
    A String is a sequence of characters.
    String str = "hello";
    IMPORTANT: String is IMMUTABLE.  Once created → cannot be changed
    String s = "hello";
    s.concat(" world");  // creates new object

  Internal Working of String:
    String Pool (Heap Memory Optimization)
    String s1 = "java";
    String s2 = "java"; -> Only one object is created in String Constant Pool
    But:  String s3 = new String("java"); -> Creates new object in heap
    
  Why String is Immutable?
      Security (used in URL, DB, file paths)
      Thread-safe
      Caching (String Pool)
      Performance
      
   Important String Methods
        str.length();
        str.charAt(0);
        str.substring(1, 3);
        str.equals("abc");
        str.equalsIgnoreCase("ABC");
        str.toUpperCase();
        str.toLowerCase();
        str.trim();
        str.contains("el");
        str.replace("l", "x");
        str.split(" ");
  
    String str = "hello world";
    String substring(int beginIndex) -> System.out.println(str.substring(6));     // world
    String substring(int beginIndex, int endIndex) -> System.out.println(str.substring(0, 5));  // hello
    beginIndex = inclusive
    endIndex = exclusive
      
    String[] split(String regex) -String[] 
    String[] split(String regex, int limit)
    🔹 Example 1 (Simple split)
        String str = "a,b,c";
        String[] arr = str.split(",");
        System.out.println(Arrays.toString(arr));   // [a, b, c]
    🔹 Example 2 (Regex split)
        String str = "a1b2c3";
        String[] arr = str.split("\\d");
        System.out.println(Arrays.toString(arr));  // [a, b, c]-> \\d → regex for digits  
    🔹 Example 3 (Split by multiple delimiters)
        String str = "a,b;c";
        String[] arr = str.split("[,;]");
        System.out.println(Arrays.toString(arr)); // [a, b, c]
    ⚠️ Common Mistake (VERY IMPORTANT)
        String str = "a.b.c"; 
        str.split(".");   // ❌ WRONG  "." in regex means any character
        ✔ Correct way: str.split("\\.");
    🔹 Example with limit
        String str = "a,b,c,d";
        String[] arr = str.split(",", 2);
        System.out.println(Arrays.toString(arr));// [a, b,c,d]
      
String vs StringBuilder vs StringBuffer:
        Feature	    String	        StringBuilder    StringBuffer
        Mutability	❌ Immutable	  ✅ Mutable      ✅ Mutable
        Thread-safe	❌	            ❌              ✅
        Performance	Slow	          Fastest	         Slower than Builder

    StringBuilder sb = new StringBuilder("hello");
    sb.append(" world");

    System.out.println(sb);  // hello world

  String Comparison (VERY IMPORTANT):
    String a = "java";
    String b = "java";
    
    System.out.println(a == b);        // true (same reference)
    System.out.println(a.equals(b));   // true (value compare)
    String x = new String("java");
    String y = new String("java");
    
    System.out.println(x == y);        // false
    System.out.println(x.equals(y));   // true

   Memory Diagram (Concept):
    String Pool: "java"  <-- s1, s2
     Heap: new String("java") <-- s3

Array vs String (Key Differences)
        Feature	      Array	              String
        Type	        Data Structure	    Class
        Mutability	  Mutable	            Immutable
        Size	        Fixed	              Fixed (but new object created on change)
        Storage	      Contiguous memory  	Heap + String Pool
        Methods	      Limited            	Rich API

  1. Why array is faster than ArrayList? -No resizing, direct memory access
  2. Why String is immutable?-> Security + caching + thread safety
  3. Why use StringBuilder? -> For heavy string modification (performance)
  4. How String pool improves performance?-> Reuses objects → reduces memory usage
